As we can see from the simplified syscall implementations in Figure~\ref{fig:motivating_code}, an attacker can invoke \texttt{syscall\_A()} to potentially trigger 3 primitives: UAF Write, Arbitrary Address Write (AAW) and Control Flow Hijacking (CFH). On the other hand, invoking \texttt{syscall\_B()} will potentially trigger 2 primitives: AAW and CFH.

To influence the behaviors of the vulnerability and steer the kernel into different execution paths, the attacker can choose the bug-triggering syscall (i.e., \texttt{syscall\_A()}, \texttt{syscall\_B()}, or modify syscall arguments such as \textcolor{DarkGreen}{\texttt{args1}} to alter the vulnerability context. Furthermore, the attacker can leverage heap spray to manipulate the memory pointed to by the dangling \textcolor{red}{\texttt{obj}} pointer, thereby influencing the execution paths in \texttt{syscall\_B()}.

Suppose the attacker's goal is to hijack the control flow of the kernel by making use of a CFH primitive. One option is to pick \texttt{syscall\_A()} and spray controllable data to occupy the freed memory beforehand. However, this will definitely trigger the UAF Write, denoted as \circled{2} in Figure~\ref{fig:motivating}, and there is a possibility that an AAW side effect may be triggered as well, denoted as \circled{5} --- we use the term AAW side effect to refer to an undesirable effect where a pointer corrupted by attacker-sprayed memory is dereferenced (an attacker may not know a valid address to overwrite the pointer with). 
%While AAW typically implies intentional control over the write address, we extend the term to include such unintended address write). 
In this case, we consider the CFH primitive (\circled{6}) the desired primitive (CFH) and UAF write (\circled{2}) and AAW (\circled{6}) side effects. This is because they both can lead to kernel crashes. The UAF write can potentially corrupt important data belonging to the sprayed object, making the use of the sprayed object crash. The AAW side effect is even more serious because it can easily lead to crashes if the corrupted pointer \texttt{obj->p1} points to an invalid address.
