\subsection{Effects, Primitives, and Side Effects} \label{chap:eps}

In this section, we define a few key terms to help clarify the description of the rest of the paper. 

\textbf{Effects} refer to any unintended memory operations directly or indirectly caused by the vulnerability.

\textbf{Primitives} are a subset of effects, denoting the specific effects that attackers choose to carry out an exploit. In the motivating example, if the attacker selects the CFH effect, e.g., to conduct return-oriented programming, then we consider the CFH effect to be a primitive. Meanwhile, 

\textbf{Side effects} are defined as the remaining effects that are not picked for exploit construction.
Three observations on them are crucial for handling side effects:

\noindent\textbf{1. Primitives Are Chosen}: Whether an effect is considered a primitive depends on the attacker's strategy. For example, although CFH is often seen as powerful (e.g., for ROP), if the attacker chooses to use UAF Write to corrupt heap objects instead, the CFH would become a side effect, which can lead to crashes if we do not overwrite it with a legitimate kernel function address.

\noindent\textbf{2. Primitives are Mutually Exclusive}: Attackers usually use only one primitive per bug triggering, as different primitives need different memory layouts, which are hard to set up at once. If two are needed, they typically trigger the bug twice. So, once a primitive is chosen, other effects in the same execution become side effects.

\noindent\textbf{3. Some Side Effects Are More Lethal}: Not all side effects are equally harmful. Those involving pointer dereferences are much more likely to crash the kernel due to invalid memory access. For instance, CFH and AAW are more dangerous than UAF Write.

%\zhiyun{need to define purified primitives or clean primitives. I personally prefer clean because purified assumes it requires work to be clean (but a primitive may naturally be clean and does not require purification).}

%\zhiyun{The definitions here are much clearer (and more reasonable) than the ones in the opening paragraph. We should improve the opening paragraph to match the actual definition.}

Thus, in this paper, we \textbf{do not} determine primitives based on the behaviors of effects. Instead, we leave the freedom of choosing the exploit strategy to the exploit developer and treat all effects as potential primitives equally. Thus, for each of them, we try to find strategies to solve other effects for it. Also, we prioritize solving side effects involving pointer dereference.


